In Japanese culture, '''π/''' ({{nihongo2|パイスラッシュ}} or {{nihongo2|パイスラ}}, Romanized ''Paisurasshu'', ''pai sura'', ''paisura'' or '''''pai slash''''') denotes the appearance of a woman's breasts bisected by a diagonal strap (slash), such as an automobile [[Seat belt#Three-point|shoulder harness]] or [[Handbag|purse]] worn cross-body.<ref>Your Handbag Strap Has a Sexual Connotation (In Japan), Splinter, [[Gizmodo Media Group]], October 28, 2013</ref> The term involves a play on words of the Japanese word for breasts, ''oppai''.<ref>{{citation|title=パイスラ|publisher=[[Weblio]]|language=English and Japanese|url=http://ejje.weblio.jp/content/パイスラ}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Handbag strap breast slash bosom books big seller|author=Mark Weitzman|work=Let's Japan|date=August 31, 2013|url=http://letsjapan.mark-weitzman.com/handbag-strap-breast-slash-bosom-books-big-seller/}}</ref> The term began to appear on the Internet in June 2006.<ref>[[Google Trends]], "パイスラ"/"パイスラッシュ"</ref>

