{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Red vineyards.jpg | painting_alignment = right | title = Red Vineyards near Arles | alt = La Vigne rouge | artist = [[Vincent van Gogh]] | year = 1888 | catalogue = {{Flatlist}} *[[Jacob Baart de la Faille|F495]] *[[Jan Hulsker|JH1626]] {{Endflatlist}} | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 75 | width_metric = 93 | height_imperial = 29.5 | width_imperial = 36.6 | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = Moscow | museum = [[Pushkin Museum of Fine Arts]] }}
'''''The Red Vineyards near Arles''''' is an oil painting by the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] painter [[Vincent van Gogh]], executed on a privately primed [[French Standard Sizes for Oil paintings|Toile de 30]] piece of burlap in early November 1888. It depicts workers in a [[vineyard]], and is believed to be the only van Gogh painting sold during his lifetime.
It has been listed among the artist's major works.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lj75DAAAQBAJ&pg=PT89|title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide Russia|publisher=Penguin|date=2016|isbn=1465462635|quote=[...] but the real masterpieces are upstairs. On the second floor are paintings by Vincent van Gogh, including ''The Red Vineyard at Arles'' (1888) and ''Prisoners Exercising'' (1890) [...]}}</ref>
==History== ''The Red Vineyard'' was exhibited for the first time at the [[Vincent van Gogh's display at Les XX, 1890|annual exhibition of Les XX, 1890]] in Brussels, and sold for 400 Francs (equal to about [[USD|$]]2,000 today) to [[Anna Boch]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://annaboch.com|title=Anna Boch.com Impressionist, patron of many artists|website=annaboch.com|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> an impressionist painter, member of [[Les XX]] and art collector from Belgium;<ref>Hulsker (1980), 356</ref><ref>Pickvance (1984), 168–169;206</ref> Anna was the sister of [[Eugène Boch]], another impressionist painter and a friend of Van Gogh, too, who had painted Boch's portrait (''[[Portrait of Eugene Boch|Le Peintre aux Étoiles]]'') in [[Arles]], in autumn 1888.
It was acquired by the famous Russian collector [[Ivan Morozov|Sergei Shchukin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://annaboch.com/theredvineyard/|title=The Red Vineyard by Vincent van Gogh - World's most valuable painting|website=annaboch.com|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> but was later nationalised by the [[Bolsheviks]] with the rest of his collection, which eventually passed to the [[Pushkin Museum of Fine Arts]] in [[Moscow]], where is resides today.
